---
import Layout from '../../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import SiteHeader from '../../../components/SiteHeader.astro';
import TopicNext from '../../../components/TopicNext.astro';
import MadeByKaj from '../../../components/MadeByKaj.astro';

const basePath = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;

const nextTopics = [
	{ slug: 'star-clusters', title: 'Star clusters: families of stars' },
	{ slug: 'radio-bubble', title: 'The radio bubble' },
	{ slug: 'astrophage', title: 'Astrophage' },
];
---

<Layout
	title="The Hertzsprung-Russell diagram | Learn | Found in Space"
	description="Follow a guided HR diagram lesson built from real Gaia data. Compare all-sky, directional, and volume-limited samples from the Sun to see how stellar populations change."
>
	<SiteHeader section="Learn" />

	<main class="page">
		<section class="intro">
			<nav class="breadcrumb" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
				<a href={`${basePath}learn/`}>Learn</a>
				<span class="breadcrumb__sep" aria-hidden="true">›</span>
				<span>The Hertzsprung-Russell diagram</span>
			</nav>
			<p class="eyebrow">Learn</p>
			<h1>The Hertzsprung-Russell diagram</h1>
			<p class="lede">
				The HR diagram is not a map of where stars are. It is a map of what stars
				<em>are</em>: hot or cool, bright or faint, youthful, swollen, or nearly dead.
				In this guided path we keep the Sun fixed and change the way we sample the Gaia stars
				around us, so the structure of the diagram emerges step by step.
			</p>
		</section>

		<section class="body-section prose">
			<h2>What this lesson is comparing</h2>
			<p>
				Every step below uses the same underlying Gaia catalogue, but samples it in a different
				way. First we take a magnitude-limited all-sky view from the Sun. Then we keep the same
				magnitude limit but only plot the stars in front of us, so the direction of the camera
				starts to matter. Finally we switch to a volume-limited census of nearby space, where
				faint dwarfs are no longer excluded just because they are hard to see.
			</p>
			<p>
				The axes are both backwards. Temperature decreases from left to right, so hot blue-white
				stars are on the left and cool red stars are on the right. Absolute magnitude decreases
				upward, so the intrinsically brightest stars sit at the top of the plot.
			</p>
			<p>
				Scroll through the lesson below to let the script change the sampling mode and camera
				direction for you. The star view and the HR diagram stay side by side, so you can see
				how the sky in front of us translates into the population on the diagram. We begin in
				the solar neighbourhood, then leave the Sun behind to expose the catalogue's selection
				effects, and finally fly into real star clusters with very different stellar histories.
			</p>
		</section>

		<div class="narrated-tour hr-tour" data-hr-tour>
			<div class="narrated-tour__chapters">
				<section class="narrated-tour__chapter" data-step="all-stars">
					<p class="narrated-tour__chapter-eyebrow">Step 1 · Sun · all-sky sample</p>
					<h2 class="narrated-tour__chapter-title">The all-stars view reveals the big structure</h2>
					<p>
						We begin at the Sun, but the first sample ignores viewing direction completely.
						It plots every star in the Gaia set that is bright enough to clear the apparent
						magnitude limit, no matter where it lies on the sky.
					</p>
					<p>
						That is enough to reveal the two most obvious landmarks. The broad diagonal band
						is the <strong>main sequence</strong>, where stars spend most of their lives
						fusing hydrogen. The plume rising up on the cool side is the
						<strong>red giant branch</strong>, made of stars that have exhausted their core
						hydrogen and expanded into luminous, cooler giants.
					</p>
					<p>
						The Sun sits roughly in the middle of the main sequence: ordinary, stable, and
						unexceptional. What this first view does <em>not</em> show fairly is how common
						faint dwarfs really are, because a magnitude-limited survey naturally favours the
						stars that shine brightest.
					</p>
				</section>

				<section class="narrated-tour__chapter" data-step="inner-plane">
					<p class="narrated-tour__chapter-eyebrow">Step 2 · View only · inner galactic plane</p>
					<h2 class="narrated-tour__chapter-title">Looking into the inner plane shifts the mix</h2>
					<p>
						Now we keep the Sun fixed and keep the same magnitude limit, but only plot the
						stars that lie <em>in front of the camera</em>. The HR diagram becomes a directional
						slice through the stellar population rather than an all-sky average.
					</p>
					<p>
						Pointing into the inner galactic plane gives us a denser, younger-looking sample.
						This is where the Milky Way's disc is richest in star-forming material and where
						young, luminous stars are easiest to find. The bright upper main sequence becomes
						more prominent because those massive stars light up the disc even when they are
						rare.
					</p>
				</section>

				<section class="narrated-tour__chapter" data-step="out-of-plane">
					<p class="narrated-tour__chapter-eyebrow">Step 3 · View only · high galactic latitude</p>
					<h2 class="narrated-tour__chapter-title">Out of the plane, evolved stars stand out more</h2>
					<p>
						Rotate the view away from the galactic plane and the population changes again.
						There are simply fewer young, massive stars far above or below the thin disc where
						star formation is concentrated.
					</p>
					<p>
						The sample now leans toward older, more evolved stars. The giant branch remains,
						but the bright hot end of the main sequence thins out. We are not changing stellar
						physics here. We are changing <em>which part of the galaxy</em> contributes stars
						to the diagram.
					</p>
				</section>

				<section class="narrated-tour__chapter" data-step="local-volume">
					<p class="narrated-tour__chapter-eyebrow">Step 4 · Volume mode · local census</p>
					<h2 class="narrated-tour__chapter-title">A local volume flips the bias</h2>
					<p>
						Finally we abandon the magnitude cutoff and instead include every star within a
						fixed sphere around the Sun. This is a much fairer census of our immediate
						neighbourhood.
					</p>
					<p>
						The spectacular super-bright stars mostly disappear, not because they ceased to
						exist, but because there are none that close to us. In their place the lower main
						sequence fills up with enormous numbers of faint dwarfs. That is the real local
						population asserting itself: the Milky Way is dominated by small, cool stars.
					</p>
					<p>
						This local benchmark matters, because the next few chapters leave the Sun. Once we
						move away from the telescope that collected the data, we start to see which
						features in the diagram are robust stellar demographics and which ones depend on
						what Gaia was actually able to detect from home.
					</p>
				</section>

				<section class="narrated-tour__chapter" data-step="away-volume">
					<p class="narrated-tour__chapter-eyebrow">Step 5 · Volume mode · ~100 pc from the Sun</p>
					<h2 class="narrated-tour__chapter-title">The white dwarfs thin out for observational reasons</h2>
					<p>
						Now we fly only about 100 parsecs away. That is not far enough for the underlying
						stellar population to change dramatically. We are still in the same broad region of
						the galactic disc.
					</p>
					<p>
						And yet the white-dwarf sequence already starts to weaken. The key point is that
						this is <em>not</em> because white dwarfs suddenly become rare 100 parsecs from the
						Sun. It is because Gaia observed from the Solar System. Many faint white dwarfs
						that would belong in a complete local census around this new position were already
						too dim for Gaia to measure from the Sun in the first place.
					</p>
					<p>
						This is the lesson's first major warning label: when we move the observer through
						the dataset, we are moving through a catalogue whose selection function is still
						anchored at Earth.
					</p>
				</section>

				<section class="narrated-tour__chapter" data-step="pleiades">
					<p class="narrated-tour__chapter-eyebrow">Step 6 · Young open cluster · Pleiades</p>
					<h2 class="narrated-tour__chapter-title">A young cluster collapses the diagram onto the main sequence</h2>
					<p>
						Next we fly into the Pleiades, one of the nearest young open clusters. Here the
						population is no longer a field mixture of many ages. Most of the stars were born
						together, from the same cloud, at almost the same time.
					</p>
					<p>
						That is why the HR diagram tightens into a much cleaner sequence. The cluster is
						young enough that its bright blue stars are still alive, and there has not yet
						been time to build up a large evolved population. Instead of a broad field diagram,
						we get something much closer to a single age track written across the main
						sequence.
					</p>
				</section>

				<section class="narrated-tour__chapter" data-step="hyades">
					<p class="narrated-tour__chapter-eyebrow">Step 7 · Older open cluster · Hyades</p>
					<h2 class="narrated-tour__chapter-title">An older cluster shows the turn-off marching downward</h2>
					<p>
						The Hyades are still an open cluster, but they are much older than the Pleiades.
						That extra time matters. The most massive stars have already exhausted their core
						hydrogen and left the upper main sequence.
					</p>
					<p>
						Compared with the Pleiades, the turn-off point has moved downward to lower masses,
						and evolved giants become more obvious. This is why clusters are such powerful
						stellar clocks: in a population of one age, the place where stars peel away from
						the main sequence tells you how long the cluster has been evolving.
					</p>
				</section>

				<section class="narrated-tour__chapter" data-step="omega-cen">
					<p class="narrated-tour__chapter-eyebrow">Step 8 · Globular cluster · Omega Centauri · 100 pc sample</p>
					<h2 class="narrated-tour__chapter-title">A globular cluster is an ancient stellar population</h2>
					<p>
						Finally we jump to Omega Centauri, the same globular cluster from the star-clusters
						lesson. This is a completely different stellar environment: far older, denser, and
						more dominated by low-mass survivors.
					</p>
					<p>
						For this final stop we widen the sample to 100 parsecs. Omega Centauri is much
						more extended than the nearby open clusters on this scale, so a larger bubble gives
						us a more representative view of the cluster rather than just a tiny local patch.
					</p>
					<p>
						The hot, massive end of the main sequence is gone because those stars died billions
						of years ago. What remains is an elderly population: faint low-mass stars, a strong
						giant branch, and the evolved remnants of a system that formed long before the
						Sun. Even without perfect completeness, the contrast with the local field and the
						open clusters is stark.
					</p>
				</section>

				<div class="narrated-tour__spacer" aria-hidden="true"></div>
			</div>

			<div class="narrated-tour__viewer-col">
				<div class="narrated-tour__viewer-sticky">
					<div class="narrated-tour__nav">
						<button type="button" class="narrated-tour__nav-button" data-step-fly="all-stars">All sky</button>
						<button type="button" class="narrated-tour__nav-button" data-step-fly="inner-plane">Inner disc</button>
						<button type="button" class="narrated-tour__nav-button" data-step-fly="out-of-plane">High lat</button>
						<button type="button" class="narrated-tour__nav-button" data-step-fly="local-volume">Local</button>
						<button type="button" class="narrated-tour__nav-button" data-step-fly="away-volume">+100 pc</button>
						<button type="button" class="narrated-tour__nav-button" data-step-fly="pleiades">Pleiades</button>
						<button type="button" class="narrated-tour__nav-button" data-step-fly="hyades">Hyades</button>
						<button type="button" class="narrated-tour__nav-button" data-step-fly="omega-cen">ω Cen</button>
					</div>

					<div
						class="narrated-tour__viewer-shell hr-tour__viewer-shell"
						data-hr-diagram-viewer
						data-topic="hr-diagram-lesson"
						data-show-hr="true"
					>
						<section class="hr-tour__pane">
							<div class="hr-tour__pane-head">
								<span class="tag">Star view</span>
							</div>
							<div class="hr-tour__space-view" data-hr-diagram-viewer-shell></div>
						</section>

						<section class="hr-tour__pane">
							<div class="hr-tour__pane-head">
								<span class="tag">HR diagram</span>
							</div>
							<canvas class="hr-tour__canvas" data-hr-diagram-viewer-hr aria-label="Live HR diagram"></canvas>
						</section>
					</div>

					<span class="narrated-tour__status" data-hr-tour-status>Loading…</span>
				</div>
			</div>
		</div>

		<section class="explore-section">
			<h2>What to compare across the full lesson</h2>
			<p>
				The same plot is doing two jobs at once: revealing stellar evolution and revealing the
				selection effects baked into the catalogue.
			</p>
			<div class="explore-grid">
				<article class="panel">
					<p class="panel__eyebrow">Bias</p>
					<h3>Moving the observer does not move the telescope</h3>
					<p>
						When you fly away from the Sun, you are not creating a brand-new Gaia survey from
						that location. You are reusing a catalogue observed from Earth, so faint stars can
						drop out for purely observational reasons.
					</p>
				</article>

				<article class="panel">
					<p class="panel__eyebrow">Youth</p>
					<h3>The Pleiades stay close to a clean main sequence</h3>
					<p>
						A young cluster has had little time to evolve away from the main sequence. Its HR
						diagram is much tighter than the mixed-age field near the Sun.
					</p>
				</article>

				<article class="panel">
					<p class="panel__eyebrow">Age</p>
					<h3>The Hyades show the turn-off shifting downward</h3>
					<p>
						Compared with the Pleiades, the Hyades have already lost their hottest main-sequence
						stars. That missing upper end is the signature of a more evolved cluster.
					</p>
				</article>

				<article class="panel">
					<p class="panel__eyebrow">Extremes</p>
					<h3>Omega Centauri is a very old population in a very different setting</h3>
					<p>
						A globular cluster pushes the lesson to its oldest end-state: dense, ancient, and
						depleted of massive stars. Its diagram should feel nothing like the local field.
					</p>
				</article>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="body-section prose">
			<h2>Artefacts in the diagram</h2>
			<p>
				If you look carefully at the cool edge of the diagram, you will notice features that
				come not from stellar physics but from how the data is processed.
			</p>

			<h3>The ~2 700 K wall</h3>
			<p>
				The main sequence appears to hit a hard vertical wall at around 2 700 K. This is real,
				but it is a pipeline artefact, not a physical boundary. Most faint red stars in the Gaia
				catalogue lack a spectroscopic temperature estimate. For those stars the pipeline falls
				back to converting the Gaia BP&ndash;RP colour index to an effective temperature using the
				<a
					href="https://github.com/Found-in-Space/pipeline/blob/main/src/foundinspace/pipeline/common/photometry.py"
					class="link--gold"
				>
					Ballesteros (2012) relation
				</a>.
				That conversion clamps the B&ndash;V colour index at 2.5 to avoid singularities, which
				maps every star redder than BP&ndash;RP&nbsp;&asymp;&nbsp;3.0 to the same temperature of
				roughly 2 725 K. The result is a hard pile-up at that value. Real M dwarfs extend to
				cooler temperatures, but this dataset cannot distinguish them.
			</p>

			<h3>The 5 800 K default</h3>
			<p>
				A small number of stars have no usable temperature from any source: no Gaia
				spectroscopic estimate, no BP&ndash;RP colour, no B&ndash;V. The pipeline
				<a
					href="https://github.com/Found-in-Space/pipeline/blob/main/src/foundinspace/pipeline/gaia/photometry.py"
					class="link--gold"
				>
					assigns these a default of 5 800 K
				</a>
				(roughly solar). You may notice a faint vertical streak at the Sun's temperature. That
				is these default-temperature stars landing at the same x-coordinate. The effect is subtle
				but visible when a larger local volume is loaded.
			</p>
		</section>

		<section class="gaia-note">
			<div class="panel panel--accent">
				<p class="panel__eyebrow">Beyond this lesson</p>
				<h3>Gaia made the modern HR diagram a precision tool</h3>
				<p>
					Gaia has measured positions, distances, and colours for nearly two billion stars. In
					those enormous HR diagrams, astronomers can see fine structure invisible in smaller
					surveys: split white-dwarf sequences, crystallisation pile-ups, and the unresolved
					binary sequence just above the main sequence. Each faint ridge is another piece of
					stellar physics hiding in a scatter plot.
				</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<TopicNext topics={nextTopics} />

		<MadeByKaj />
	</main>
</Layout>

<script>
	import {
		DEFAULT_HR_MAG_LIMIT,
		DEFAULT_HR_VOLUME_RADIUS,
		GALACTIC_NORTH_TARGET_PC,
		INNER_GALACTIC_PLANE_TARGET_PC,
		mountHrDiagramViewer,
	} from '../../../scripts/hr-diagram-viewer.js';
	import { setupNarratedTour } from '../../../scripts/narrated-tour.js';
	import {
		HYADES_CENTER_PC,
		OMEGA_CEN_CENTER_PC,
		PLEIADES_CENTER_PC,
		SOLAR_ORIGIN_PC,
	} from '@found-in-space/skykit';

	const tourRoot = document.querySelector('[data-hr-tour]');
	const viewerRoot = document.querySelector('[data-hr-diagram-viewer]');
	const statusEl = document.querySelector('[data-hr-tour-status]');
	const chapters = tourRoot?.querySelectorAll('.narrated-tour__chapter[data-step]') ?? [];
	const navButtons = tourRoot?.querySelectorAll('[data-step-fly]') ?? [];
	const OFFSET_SAMPLE_PC = { x: 80, y: 60, z: 0 };
	// The field and open-cluster chapters use a consistent 25 pc bubble.
	const LESSON_VOLUME_RADIUS_PC = DEFAULT_HR_VOLUME_RADIUS;
	const OMEGA_CEN_VOLUME_RADIUS_PC = 100;

	const SCENES = {
		'all-stars': {
			observerPc: SOLAR_ORIGIN_PC,
			targetPc: INNER_GALACTIC_PLANE_TARGET_PC,
			mode: 0,
			magLimit: DEFAULT_HR_MAG_LIMIT,
		},
		'inner-plane': {
			observerPc: SOLAR_ORIGIN_PC,
			targetPc: INNER_GALACTIC_PLANE_TARGET_PC,
			mode: 2,
			magLimit: DEFAULT_HR_MAG_LIMIT,
		},
		'out-of-plane': {
			observerPc: SOLAR_ORIGIN_PC,
			targetPc: GALACTIC_NORTH_TARGET_PC,
			mode: 2,
			magLimit: DEFAULT_HR_MAG_LIMIT,
		},
		'local-volume': {
			observerPc: SOLAR_ORIGIN_PC,
			targetPc: INNER_GALACTIC_PLANE_TARGET_PC,
			mode: 1,
			radius: LESSON_VOLUME_RADIUS_PC,
			volumeRenderStrategy: 'strict',
		},
		'away-volume': {
			observerPc: OFFSET_SAMPLE_PC,
			targetPc: SOLAR_ORIGIN_PC,
			mode: 1,
			radius: LESSON_VOLUME_RADIUS_PC,
			travelTimeSecs: 4,
			volumeRenderStrategy: 'progressive',
			dwellMs: 4_000,
			recenterSpeed: 0.05,
		},
		pleiades: {
			targetPc: PLEIADES_CENTER_PC,
			orbitCenter: PLEIADES_CENTER_PC,
			mode: 1,
			radius: LESSON_VOLUME_RADIUS_PC,
			orbitRadius: 10,
			angularSpeed: 0.18,
			travelTimeSecs: 5,
			volumeRenderStrategy: 'progressive',
			dwellMs: 5_000,
			recenterSpeed: 0.06,
		},
		hyades: {
			targetPc: HYADES_CENTER_PC,
			orbitCenter: HYADES_CENTER_PC,
			mode: 1,
			radius: LESSON_VOLUME_RADIUS_PC,
			orbitRadius: 8,
			angularSpeed: 0.22,
			travelTimeSecs: 5,
			volumeRenderStrategy: 'progressive',
			dwellMs: 5_000,
			recenterSpeed: 0.06,
		},
		'omega-cen': {
			targetPc: OMEGA_CEN_CENTER_PC,
			orbitCenter: OMEGA_CEN_CENTER_PC,
			mode: 1,
			radius: OMEGA_CEN_VOLUME_RADIUS_PC,
			travelRadiusPc: LESSON_VOLUME_RADIUS_PC,
			orbitRadius: 60,
			angularSpeed: 0.08,
			travelTimeSecs: 5,
			preloadVolumeTunnel: true,
			preloadVolumeTunnelRadiusPc: LESSON_VOLUME_RADIUS_PC*1.5,
			preloadVolumeBubble: true,
			preloadVolumeBubbleRadiusPc: OMEGA_CEN_VOLUME_RADIUS_PC,
			backgroundPreloadOnMount: true,
			backgroundPreloadAnchorPc: HYADES_CENTER_PC,
			backgroundPreloadTimeoutMs: 2_500,
			volumeRenderStrategy: 'progressive',
			dwellMs: 6_000,
			recenterSpeed: 0.04,
		},
	};

	if (tourRoot && viewerRoot) {
		mountHrDiagramViewer(viewerRoot).then((viewer) => {
			setupNarratedTour({
				root: tourRoot,
				chapters,
				navButtons,
				getChapterId(chapter) {
					return chapter.dataset.step;
				},
				getNavButtonId(button) {
					return button.dataset.stepFly;
				},
				activate(id) {
					const scene = SCENES[id];
					if (scene) {
						viewer.applyScene(scene).catch((err) => {
							console.error('[website:hr-diagram-tour]', err);
						});
					}
				},
				statusEl,
				initialId: 'all-stars',
				desktopStatus: 'Scroll to travel from the Sun to clusters and compare the HR diagram.',
				phoneStatus: '',
			});

			for (const scene of Object.values(SCENES)) {
				if (!scene?.backgroundPreloadOnMount) {
					continue;
				}
				viewer.scheduleScenePreload(scene, {
					anchorObserverPc: scene.backgroundPreloadAnchorPc ?? SOLAR_ORIGIN_PC,
					delayMs: scene.backgroundPreloadDelayMs ?? 0,
					timeoutMs: scene.backgroundPreloadTimeoutMs ?? 2_000,
				});
			}
		}).catch((err) => {
			console.error('[website:hr-diagram-tour]', err);
			if (statusEl) statusEl.textContent = err instanceof Error ? err.message : String(err);
		});
	}
</script>

<style>
	.page {
		position: relative;
		min-height: 100vh;
		padding-top: 3.5rem;
	}

	.intro {
		max-width: 48rem;
		padding: 2rem 0 0;
	}

	.intro h1 {
		margin: 0;
		max-width: 16ch;
		font-size: clamp(2.4rem, 6vw, 4.2rem);
		line-height: 1.02;
		letter-spacing: -0.03em;
	}

	.body-section {
		max-width: 48rem;
		padding: 2.5rem 0 1rem;
	}

	.hr-tour {
		--fis-tour-shell-height: clamp(22rem, 58vh, 34rem);
		--fis-tour-phone-shell-height: clamp(15rem, 38svh, 18rem);
	}

	.hr-tour__viewer-shell {
		display: grid;
		grid-template-columns: repeat(2, minmax(0, 1fr));
		gap: 0.65rem;
		padding: 0.75rem;
		align-items: stretch;
	}

	.hr-tour__pane {
		display: flex;
		flex-direction: column;
		gap: 0.5rem;
		min-width: 0;
		min-height: 0;
		padding: 0.5rem;
		border: 1px solid var(--fis-line);
		border-radius: calc(var(--fis-radius) - 0.3rem);
		background: var(--fis-panel);
	}

	.hr-tour__pane-head {
		display: flex;
		align-items: center;
		justify-content: flex-start;
	}

	.hr-tour__space-view,
	.hr-tour__canvas {
		flex: 1;
		width: 100%;
		min-height: 0;
		border-radius: calc(var(--fis-radius) - 0.55rem);
		background: var(--fis-bg-deep);
	}

	.hr-tour__space-view {
		position: relative;
		overflow: hidden;
		touch-action: none;
		cursor: grab;
	}

	.hr-tour__canvas {
		display: block;
		border: 1px solid var(--fis-line);
	}

	.hr-tour__space-view:active {
		cursor: grabbing;
	}

